== The Golden Chain of Homer: Book II
_by Anton Josef Kirchweger (attributed), c. 1723 — IGF / Justitius Edition, Inner Garden Foundation, 2025_

#hm-note[
  Book II is the practical counterpart to Book I. Where Book I traced the *descent* of Spirit into Matter, Book II shows the *return*: how Nature destroys Her own creations through putrefaction, and how Art can assist and accelerate that destruction to produce, from the wreckage, a Fifth Nature more perfect than anything that came before. The pinnacle is Chapter V — the *Dismemberment of the Chaotic Water* — which is simultaneously the most detailed spagyric protocol in the work and a philosophical proof that the same procedure applies equally to every animal, plant, and mineral subject. The student who masters Chapter V has the key to all three kingdoms.
]

=== Introduction: The Return and the Three Ways of Working
Book II opens by reversing the generative direction of Book I. The four chapters on destruction mirror the four elemental kingdoms. The philosophical anchor: *"What a thing is born of, into the same it can be changed back: Ex quo aliquid fit, in illud rursus resolvitur."*

The author identifies three distinct *ways* of performing the dismemberment and reunion, distinguished by their treatment of the faeces (the fixed coal / Caput Mortuum):
+ *Via Prima — Sine Separatione Faecum Crudi:* Without separating impurities; the coal is retained and worked into the conjunction directly. Fast, complete, includes all inner essences.
+ *Via Naturae Ipsissima — The Way of Nature Herself:* Mirrors Nature's own macrocosmic impregnation/desiccation cycle; no violent calcination; the earth is dried by gentle sun-like heat and repeatedly imbued with moisture, never burned to coal.
+ *Via Faecum Separatoria:* The classical alchemical three-separation-and-reunion, with the coal calcined to ash, the salt extracted, and the three rectified components crystallised into a Quinta Essentia. Most familiar to traditional practitioners; slightly slower but with a cleanly white and crystallised result.

All three yield the same Magisterium and Quinta Essentia; the artist chooses according to their equipment, time, and temperament.

=== Chapter I: How Nature Returns the Altered (Universal Seed)
*The Circular Return:* The universal seed, having been determined into animal, plant, or mineral form, is ultimately returned to the undetermined state by the same forces that created it — putrefaction and water. The cycle is perpetual and without exception: *"Corruptio unius, generatio alterius."*

*The Speed of Return:* Animals (juicy, moist, volatile) putrefy fastest, often within hours in warm weather. Plants putrefy readily but slower (moderately moist). Minerals decay slowest — hard, dry, fixed. Yet each obeys the same law: as soon as the balsamic vital spirit departs, the inner acidity (unguarded) begins dissolving the body from within.

*Putrefaction's Mechanism:* The departure of the balsamic spirit is the trigger. The Archeus (the vital governor) departs; the volatile acid salt, formerly bound in service of life, now acts in its own nature — dissolving, liquefying, separating. "Putrefaction is the principal key for opening and locking all and everything in Nature."

*The Rotten Rainwater as the Universal Ferment:* Putrefied rainwater (the chaotic water that has become turbid and foul-smelling through its own inner action) is the prime agent for initiating or accelerating putrefaction in any subject. "Just as everything is born with and through chaotic water, so everything must be destroyed with and by it — because it is the identical fermenting ferment of all things."

*Why Putrefied Rainwater, Not Spring Water:* Ordinary spring water is too fixed and alkaline to initiate putrefaction vigorously. Rainwater, being volatile and acidic (more Acidum than Alcali), carries the aroused inner Nitre — the volatile acid principle — that acts as a ferment, awakening the subject's own internal acidity to begin its dissolution.

=== Chapter II: How Nature Destroys Animals
*The Sequence:* Balsamic spirit departs → volatile salt breathes out and spoils the air (foul stench) → everything becomes slippery, moist, wet → maggots appear (the volatile matter has become animal again) → maggots become gnats and flies (volatile becomes more volatile) → the less volatile part turns into water and earth → saltpetre and salt can be extracted from this earth.

*The Cross-Kingdom Return:* Out of these reduced animal parts, vegetables grow again. The animal kingdom *becomes vegetable in descending* — as proven in Book I. The bones and legs (most fixed parts) resist longest, requiring Nature's longest effort to return to mould and earth.

*The Maggot Experiment (demonstrating inter-kingdom transformation):* Take well-fattened maggots; lock them in a glass; feed them some stinking meat; set in lukewarm air in weak sun; close with perforated paper (air access without insects entering). Within a few days and hours, gnats and flies grow from the maggots. *This is the visible proof that the volatile part of the animal has become a new animal* — the fixed part having turned to water and salt below.

*Practical Application:* When animal remains are used as manure, they fertilise fields because their Nitre and Salt, released by putrefaction, are the very feed of plants. "Man eats bread, wine, and fruit. He produces excrements. These go back to the fields. From them his food grows again from his own excrements." In this cycle the nature of food has been completely changed inside Man (by the human Archeus) — its excrements give no indication of their prior nature. *This is the model for all philosophical fermentation.*

=== Chapter III: How Nature Destroys Vegetables
*Mechanism:* Dead leaves fall to the root, moistened by rain or dew. The implanted Spirit (now unguarded by the vital balsamic) is aroused by moisture; it warms the plant's parts; volatile parts evaporate and return to the air; fixed parts soften into slime and juice, creeping into the earth to await rebirth.

*The Transition to Animal:* If heat does not dry the dead plant too fast, the volatile part turns into worms, maggots, gnats, and flies — demonstrating that the vegetable kingdom *aims at becoming animal or volatile*. Trees suppurate and breed beetles; nests of worms arise in the excess sap. The vegetable is striving upward toward the animal.

*The Natural Calcination of Trees:* A tree's natural death proceeds through cycles of solar heat (which expands and opens the pores) followed by cold rain (which penetrates the opened pores and putrefies inside). Sun dries and opens; rain wets and infects with putrefaction; cold forces the moisture into the heartwood — this alternation continues for three human lifetimes in the case of hardwood, until the tree collapses into mould and dust.

*Gardener's Application:* Tree mould (the fine black earth produced by complete decomposition of wood over decades) is prized above all other manures. "It is too rich for common garden growths and is used only for fine flowers and aromatic herbs, because Nature has made it very subtle and turned it into a most excellent Nitre and Salt." If sawdust is taken, moistened with foul rainwater, and allowed to stand in lukewarm air, it rots quickly into a thick water; worms appear; the gardener has a ready-made ferment for his beds.

*The Putrefying Agent:* "The putrefying component is the volatile and the sour (Acidum). Rainwater is more volatile than fixed, and thus contains more Acidum than Alcali — it is the Acidum that causes putrefaction, not cold." This is the key distinction: cold preserves; warmth (via the inner Spirit) causes putrefaction.

=== Chapter IV: How Nature Destroys and Transforms Minerals
*Nature's Two Quarrymen:* (1) *Fire (Nitre / ☉ / inner central heat):* "Nitre is a pure concentrated sunbeam and the essence of the sun, its child and offspring — totally fiery in its action, although it looks ice-cold." (2) *Water (Salt / ☽ / inner central water):* "Salt is the true mother of attraction, an offspring and child of the ☽, which intensely desires Nitre as husband for begetting. Without him she cannot give birth to a perfect body."

*The Mechanism of Stone Destruction:*
The sun heats rock through; rain wets the heated rock; the cold drives the heat inward; the struggle between heat and cold (fire tries to escape, cold resists and drives it back inward) generates a destructive force that *bursts the stone into pieces*. This process, scaled over geological time: large rock → smaller pieces → sand → saline dust → salt. "If we calcine a stone in our Art and quench it in saltwater, the stone crumbles into pieces. If we calcine and chill it several more times, it will become ever smaller, yes, finally it will turn into slime and water — which Art achieves in hours, while Nature requires long years."

*The Mineral's Own Destruction:* The stone's own coagulated salt (Nitre) is aroused by rainwater seeping in — it begins acting as its own destroyer. "The stone goes to its own ruin as vegetables and minerals go to their death." Then the universal salty Spiritus Mundi from rain and dew is added and the destruction accelerates.

*Inter-Kingdom Mineral Return:* Stone → sand → saline dust → vegetable grows from it → animal eats the vegetable → animal putrefies → returns to salty nitrous water → enters the earth → becomes mineral again. The complete cycle.

*Artificial vs Natural Metals:* Metals that have been through fire (artificially separated) are much harder to return to their prime matter. They have been concentrated and stripped of their excessive moisture by the smelting process. "The more moisture has been removed from a metal by fire, the more durable it is and the harder for Nature to destroy." Yet even these are slowly attacked by arsenical and marcasitical vapours — as seen when gold buried in arsenical ground is found dissolved into an empty metallic ghost of itself.

*The Metallic Diseases and Their Cure:*
- ♄ (Lead): Melancholia
- ☽ (Silver): Phlegmatic
- ♂ (Iron): Choleric / gall and bitterness
- ♀ (Copper): Irritable liver
- ☿ (Quicksilver): Epilepsy
- ♃ (Jupiter/Tin): Dropsy (not explicitly stated for Jupiter; lead (♄) is primary melancholic)
- *The Tincture / Philosophers' Medicine* cures these metallic diseases and "elevates the purified metals into a perfect solar condition of their nature" — it does not act on the ore but on the purified metallic grain only.

"Just as all men descend from a perfect pure man's seed yet assume different shapes, complexions, properties, and diseases by chance — so metals are all born from a single seed (the universal Spiritus Mundi) but hatched into different complexions by different mother vessels, and therefore do not acquire their differences because of their substance but by chance. One is melancholic, another sanguinic, a third phlegmatic. Therefore they need a tempering medicine so that they may be brought into a solar substance."

*The Marrow Analogy:* The philosopher's tincture does not cure the ore (the sulphur, arsenic, and marcasite) but only the metal — just as a physician who can heal marrow can heal all dependent parts, while no medicine reaching only the outer bone can penetrate to the marrow. "Therefore such a solarised arsenic and marcasite can also be made into gold or silver by digestion and maturation, but not into pure gold and silver *as metals are transmuted by casting and melting*."

=== Chapter V: The Dismemberment, Separation, Reunion and Regeneration of the Chaotic Water Into a Fifth Nature — The Universal Model
*The Purpose:* Chapter V is simultaneously a *theoretical proof* (that every part of the universal seed can be separated and identified) and a *practical template* for all animal, plant, and mineral work. "According to this example all subsequent [works] must follow as children follow their mother — as animals, plants and minerals follow the universal."

*"I do not separate faeces":* The author's most radical claim — and the most practically important. Against the weight of alchemical tradition (which burns the coal/Caput Mortuum to ash, extracts the salt, and discards the rest), Kirchweger maintains: *"Nature has no impurities. Everything she has made is pure, good, and healthy, and must stay together and cannot be dispensed with."* The coal is not waste but the most fixed, most fire-resistant tincture of the whole — it is the foundation upon which the volatile must be congealed. Burning it to ash destroys the embryonic sulphur contained in it. The artist who throws away the coal has thrown away the kernel and kept the hulls.

==== The Putrefaction
Collect rainwater (thunderstorm rain preferred) in a new wooden vessel. Filter into clean glass containers. Cover with a cloth. Stand in a lukewarm place for approximately one month, covered, immobile. *When the water putrefies and becomes foul-smelling, it is ready.* Some practitioners wait until the smell has fully departed again (indicating the putrefaction cycle is complete); either is acceptable.

==== First Separation — The Volatile (Heaven + Air)
Stir the putrefied water well. Pour into a copper alembic with head and receiver. Slowly distil approximately half the liquid at gentle heat. *What passes over = the Volatile: Heaven and Air with their subtle waters.* The Acidum and Alcali (Water and Earth) remain behind.

==== Second Separation — The Phlegm (Element Water)
Continue distilling the remainder until the residue is as thick as honey (do not let it go dry — this would burn the virgin earth). *What comes over now = the Phlegm: coarse, elemental Water* — which always comes between the Volatile and the Acidum/Alcali.

==== Third Separation — Acidum and Alcali (Element Earth)
Remove the honey-thick residue from the alembic into a retort. Set in sand bath. Distil by increasing grades:
+ A sour-smelling spirit comes over → *the Acidum* (this is an extended, diluted oil — the most volatile form of the Acid principle).
+ A thick, bad-smelling oil follows → *the concentrated Acidum* (the oil = thickened Acidum; Acidum = dissolved oil; they are the same substance at different densities).
+ A black coal (Caput Mortuum / C.M.) remains → *the Alcali*: "a virgin macrocosmic Earth" — the most fixed part, ignitable like ordinary coal.
The Chaos is now divided into *four parts: Heaven, Air, Water, and Earth*, or equivalently *Volatile, Phlegm, Acidum, Alcali (coal)*.

==== Rectification of Heaven — Three Grades
Take the first distillate (the Volatile). Place in a long retort. Set in Bain Marie (water bath). Distil to half:
- First half = *Coelum seu Volatile subtilissimum* (finest Heaven) — keep separately.
- Distil the remainder to half = *Coelum seu Volatile subtilius* — keep separately.
- Distil again to half = *Coelum seu Volatile subtile* — keep separately.
*The most rectified Heaven has a great diamond-like sparkle.* The remainder (the coarse Air) is reserved for the Air rectification.

==== Rectification of Air — Three Grades
Combine the coarse Air (remainder from Heaven's rectification) with the Phlegm (from Second Separation). Place in a retort. Set in Bain Marie. Distil by grades; Air rises first:
- *Aer seu Volatile subtilissimus* — keep separately.
- *Aer subtilior* — keep separately.
- *Aer subtilis* — keep separately.
The remaining coarse Water is reserved for the Water rectification.

==== Rectification of Water — Three Grades
Take the Water remaining after Air has been separated. Set in ashes in a low retort. Distil through three increasing degrees of heat:
- *Aqua subtilissima* (subtlest Water, lowest heat)
- *Aqua subtilior* (subtler Water, medium heat)
- *Aqua subtilis* (subtle Water, stronger heat)

==== Rectification of Earth — Three Grades
Take the products of Third Separation: the coal (C.M.), the oil, and the Acidum. Pulverise the coal. Stir the oil into the coal. Place in a retort. Pour the Acidum upon it. Distil in sand:
- The Acidum distils first → *Terra seu Acidum subtilissimum*
- The oil distils next → *Terra subtilior*
- The coal remains behind → *Terra subtilis*
Total: *twelve fractions* from four elements × three grades each. These represent the twelve gradations from the most volatile Heaven to the most fixed Earth.

==== Coagulation: Reuniting the Twelve Fractions
The art of reunion is the reversal of separation. The rule: *begin with the most fixed and add progressively more volatile, one grade at a time.* Always in the same order as they separated — never in reverse.

*Step 1 — Unite the three Earths:*
Take the coal (*Terra subtilis*). Stir in the oil (*Terra subtilior*). Pour the Acidum (*Terra subtilissima*) upon it. Set in Bain Marie for four days and nights through three degrees of increasing heat. Crystals sprouting when the vessel is cooled → sign of conjunction. No more smell of acidity → sign of fixation. Then set in ashes: distil off the moisture very gently until the earth is quite dry. *The philosophical calcination and reverberation.* Repeat: imbibe with moisture → digest → distil dry → reverberate in ash → until the earth is all one single colour.

*Step 2 — Unite the three Waters upon the Earth.*
Make the dried Earth thirsty (thoroughly desiccated by reverberation). Pour the three Water fractions (combined in proportion 3:2:1, most subtle first) onto the Earth. Digest. Distil the moisture. Reverberate. Repeat the imbibition-distillation-reverberation cycle until the Earth has absorbed as much Water as it will retain. Sign: when a test crystallisation yields many crystals, the absorption is complete.

*Step 3 — Unite the three Airs and Heavens.*
First combine all three Air fractions (3:2:1). Then combine all three Heaven fractions (3:2:1). Unite Air with the impregnated Earth. Then add Heaven last. "When Heaven, Air, and Water are together it is the Ambrosial Nectar — the Drink of the Gods — which must rejuvenate our ageing process."

Pour this combined water onto the Earth (consistency of thin honey). Set in Bain Marie. Digest. Distil. Reverberate in ashes. Repeat the imbibition cycle through all grades until the Earth acquires a *fiery-red, fixed colour* stable through all four degrees of fire (Bain Marie → ashes → sand → open flame).

*The Completion Test:* Lock in two crucibles. Place in reverberating furnace for four hours through all degrees. Remove. *"Heaven and the very subtlest Water have turned into a corporeal and fixed stone."* This is the fulfilment of Hermes: *"Vis ejus integra est, si versa fuerit in terram — its power is total when it is transformed into Earth."*

