==== The Three Shorter Ways (Within Chapter V)
*Way I — Via Prima (without separation of faeces):*
Distil putrefied rainwater → extract Volatile → continue to honey thickness → Phlegma → retort for Acidum, oil and coal → powder coal → stir all oil into it → pour Acidum upon coal → retort in Bain Marie → digest 4-5 days → add Volatile → digest → distil per gradus → coagulate in ash → reverberate → imbibe with drawn-off liquor → repeat until one single colour → congeal through all grades in ashes then sand. *Result: Quintessence and Magisterium Macrocosmi.*

*Way II — Via Naturae Ipsissima (Way of Nature Herself):*
Distil all moisture from the alembic to a thick Liquor. Retort in Bain Marie, distil to the Earth (do not calcine to coal; draw off moisture only very gently so the vinegar and oil do not rise). When moisture drawn off, reverberate the earth gently through second degree. Take out, imbibe with drawn-off moisture, set in Bain Marie, distil, coagulate in ash. Repeat: reverberate, imbibe, distil, coagulate — until all one colour. Never force the fire so strongly that vinegar or oil rises. *This is the way Nature herself operates in Her macrocosmic impregnation and desiccation of the earth.*

*Way III — Via Faecum Separatoria (With Separation of Faeces, Three Steps):*
1. *Separation:* Distil Volatile (mark "A") → Phlegma to honey (mark "B") → retort for grosser Phlegma + Acidum + oil (mark "C") + oil (mark "D") → coal remains. Rectify each fraction separately.
2. *Conjunction:* Rx. Salt (Alcali) — 2 parts; Volatile spirit (A) — 6 parts; Acidum (C) — 3 parts. Pour Volatile upon Salt, then add Acidum. Distil in Bain Marie to oily consistency. Set in cellar to crystallise. Remove crystals, dry. Repeat crystallisation until no more crystals form. Dry crystals gently → the Fifth Essence (Quinta Essentia).
3. *Congealing:* Pulverise the crystals in a retort; set in sand, heat through four degrees for three hours → they flow into a salty stone (liquid as oil when hot, stone when cold). To incorporate the oil (D): mix 3 parts stone + 2 parts oil → retort in gentle ashes for four days → oil becomes fixed → repeat adding oil until the stone flows as a single unified body.

==== On the Aqua Recolacea (Phlegm) — The Deepest Teaching of Chapter V
*The central theoretical problem:* If all water contains spirit, and spirit contains water — why distil the Phlegm off at all? The author's answer is one of the most nuanced passages in the entire work:

"Water is only a cover or casing of the universal seed or spirit. Water itself is not the seed or spirit. The seed is dissolved in the Phlegm; they are one. But the spirit or seed, because it is salty and has a coagulating nature, can be coagulated much more readily than the mere Phlegm which is still an unripe and not salty seed. As long as the tasteless Phlegm is present, the seed or spirit cannot be permanently united in a body."

"But the Phlegm is never totally without spirit or power. It is an excellently purified radical moisture which consumptives should take as their beverage. When the concentrated Quintessence is taken as medicine, this Phlegm is its vehiculum — it is injected into a sick body and the concentrated spirit is again awakened by it, joining with and strengthening the sick Archeus."

*The Phlegm as the Mirror of the Evestrum:* Pour the completed Quintessence back into an alembic; pour its own Phlegma over it until the alembic is filled to the brim; set in warmth. *"You will see a wonderful sight: the Spirit or Evestrum will represent the shape of the animal as it had been previously during life."* In cold, this vanishes. The Phlegm arouses the implanted Spirit to action — this is why it should not be permanently discarded but preserved as the Spirit's own vehiculum.

*The Proof of Coagulation Speed:* Take the Spiritus Vini (alcohol, fully rectified until it ignites gunpowder). Pour it upon the fixed Alcali + coal. Draw off the moisture again: weigh the drawn-off Recolacea and compare to the original Spiritus Vini. You will find that the Recolacea weighs nearly as much as the original Spirit — meaning almost all its volume was Phlegm, with only a tiny fraction being the actual seed-salt. *This small fraction is what coagulates instantly; the vast Phlegma is what goes over empty.*

=== Chapter VI: What Is Finally To Be Concluded
*The Master Principle:* Every creature — animal, plant, mineral — must be treated in the same order and manner as the chaotic rainwater. The same six stages apply universally: (1) Putrefaction, (2) Distillation/Separation, (3) Rectification, (4) Conjunction, (5) Coagulation, (6) Fixation. Then optionally: (7) Imbibing, (8) Liquefying to wax, (9) Multiplication, (10) Fermentation.

*The Vocabulary of the Three Kingdoms Compared:*
- Volatile = Spirit / Heaven + Air / Sperma universale / the first distillate
- Acidum = Soul / Half-fixed intermediary / Acetum / Azoth / Plant vinegar / Animal urinous acid / Mineral vitriolic spirit
- Alcali = Body / Fixed Earth / Coal / Sal Tartari / Animal coal → alkaline salt / Mineral vitriol calcined → mineral salt
- Oil = Thickened Acidum (same substance, more fixed form)
- Coal = Coagulated oil (same substance, yet more fixed form)
- Ash/Salt = Calcined coal (same substance at highest fixity)
*"Coal is coagulated oil; oil is dissolved coal; the volatile spirit is diluted vinegar; vinegar is thinned oil. They are all one single substance in different degrees of fixation."*

*The Proof That Coal Is No Faeces:* Melt Sal Tartari and add coal dust — the salt immediately turns dark blue-green with the tincture of the coal. Dissolve this in Spiritus Vini; the tincture dissolves as a ruby-red or golden-yellow oil. "Here, you alchemists, you have the fruit of what you throw away!" The person who sold this extract as *Aurum Potabile Astrale* (claiming it was solar sulphur caught from the air in hot days) was actually selling the tincture of coal dust that had jumped into his melting Sal Tartari from the fire. *"What name shall I give to this one, when the thing to be dissolved stays together with the dissolvent and the fixed and volatile are inseparably joined?"*

*On Fixing:* "If you wish to fix, look first for the fixed body as the basis of fire resistance, like an architect who puts the most stable stones on the ground — afterwards he builds all kinds of things on that ground. You must take the fixed substance and afterwards congeal its own volatile upon it according to the natural order and law." The persistent error of alchemists: trying to make the tincture fiery-red and glassy without first having the glass-making substance — which they have thrown away.

*The Universal Conclusion:* "Animals are volatile plants; plants are volatile minerals; minerals are fixed plants; plants are fixed animals." The three kingdoms differ only in the degree of fixation of their common Nitre and Salt. "This is not speculation — it is directly provable by the fact that the essential oils, acids, and alkaline salts of animals, plants, and minerals are recognisable as the *same substance* in different concentrations."

=== Chapter VII: Dissection of Animals — Anatomia Animalium
*The Three Gross Fractions of Animals:* Every animal yields:
- *Volatile:* Strong, penetrating, stinking spirit + volatile salt + Phlegm (the urinous spirit that attacks the tongue and nose).
- *Acidum:* Stinking animal acid + animal oil (separated from vinegar by glass funnel / triturium).
- *Alcali:* Animal coal → calcined to ash → lixiviated → *Sal Alcali animale*.

*Putrefaction is Mandatory:* Without prior putrefaction, only an odour comes over. All powers are locked; no true separation occurs. The putrefaction unlocks the volatile salt — it is this urinous spirit that distinguishes the animal kingdom from all others in power of action.

*The Special Warning on Warm Blood:* "I tried to distil warm blood through an alembic, and the *Evestrum* of the animal appeared in the recipient in a hideous way; human blood began a rumbling noise in the alembic as if a poltergeist were in it." The advice: do not work with warm blood directly. Use instead: urine, faeces (the best, containing the full animal power), then horns, bones, nails, hair, scales, etc. Excrements contain as much virtue as the body itself — and Nature has provided them so we need not destroy the living body.

*Preparing Hard Animal Parts (Bones, Horns, Nails, Hair):* Two methods:
+ *Via Putrefactionis:* Boil the hard parts in the urine of the same animal (or human urine, or putrefied rainwater) for 24 hours to three days without interruption, until they turn into jelly. Let this jelly putrefy with further rainwater additions. Then separate and conjoin as above.
+ *Via Sicca:* Grind/file/cut the hard parts small. Put into a retort without any liquid. Distil dry through gentle grades. No Volatile rises (it has evaporated through geological drying and concentration into the Acidum and oil). Obtain Phlegm, Acidum, oil, and coal. Conjoin.

*The Volatile Salt of Plants via Animal Fermentation:* "If the plant is set to macerate and putrefy until maggots and worms grow in it, then distil with a high alembic in Bain Marie — an animal-urinous spirit will rise and the volatile salt attaches itself to the head." *The plant has become animal.* This is the simplest way to obtain the volatile salt of a plant that lacks one: allow the plant to putrefy completely, let it become animal through fermentation, then distil.

*The Conjunction of Animal Principles:*
Rx. Two parts Volatile — Six parts. Oil + Coal mixed — One part each. Acidum — Three parts.
"Pour the Volatile upon the Coal in a retort; add the Acidum. Set in Bain Marie for two days and two nights at moderate heat. Distil: the Volatile rises weakly with the Phlegm; the most volatile and acid stays at the bottom. Take this out of the Bain Marie, set in ashes to dry and coagulate. Reverberate. Imbibe with Volatile. Repeat until Quinta Essentia." 

*Sign of the Conjunction:* "When you have coagulated, the volatile, acid and alkaline parts will flow steadily together in the fire as an incombustible oil. In the air, they stand like ice. They dissolve in any moisture like sugar."

*The Principle:* Rx. Two parts Alcali; four parts Volatile; three parts Acidum. Pour Volatile upon Alcali first; add Acidum. Distil in Bain Marie to oily consistency. Cool in cellar; crystallise; remove crystals; repeat. When no more crystals form — dry, seal in retort, sand bath, heat through four degrees → flows as a stone. Smash the retort; remove the Quinta Essentia. Carry dry in a boxwood container. For use: a few grains in appropriate water or wine → dissolves like sugar and ice.

=== Chapter VIII: Anatomia Vegetabilium — Dissection of Plants
*The Three Gross Fractions of Plants:*
- *Volatile:* Burning spirit (Spiritus Vini / alcohol) + Phlegm + subtle oil.
- *Acidum:* Sharp vinegar (Acetum) + thick stinking oil.
- *Alcali:* Plant coal → calcined → Potash (Sal Tartari) + plant ashes.

*General Procedure:* Grind / cut / crush all green parts. Add putrefied rainwater, wine, or saltwater if the plant lacks sufficient juice. Or press juice and let ferment like wine. Let the paste stand in a lukewarm spot for 14 days to 3 weeks until it gives off a sour or foul smell. Distil the Volatile + soft Phlegm from an alembic (gentle heat). Dry the residue completely. Retort in sand per gradus: grosser Phlegm → Acetum (Acidum) → thick oil → coal (C.M.) remains.

*The Plant as Hermaphrodite:* "This kingdom is a true hermaphrodite and Janus which is neither animal nor mineral but both, and stands in the centre. With one eye it looks to the animal, with the other to the mineral — and it can become either animal or mineral, as Nature or the Art undertakes the process." The vegetable Acidum (vinegar, Azoth) is thus the universal intermediary — it bridges mineral Alcali and animal Volatile with equal ease.

*Therapeutic Differentiations from Plant Anatomy:*
- Plant with much Volatile (burning spirit, fragrant): heals and strengthens the natural, vital, and mental spirit.
- Plant with much Acidum (contract, astringent): heals tight limbs, muscles, sinews, bones, cartilages, viscid vessels.
- Plant with thick oil (concentrated Acidum): acts on the thicker, more coagulated parts of the body (fixes chronic diseases).
- "A highly volatile thing cannot serve as food for the fixed bones — when it reaches the body, it is immediately driven out through the pores as perspiration. An Acidum is not expelled this way but excites urine or bowel evacuation."

*The Wine Distillation as Model:* Wine is the *principal subject* of the plant kingdom — "just as the human being is the principal subject of the animal kingdom and gold is the principal subject of the mineral kingdom, wine comprises in itself generally all plant subjects and can be compared with every individual of its realm." Therefore the complete wine dissection serves as the canonical plant prototype:
+ Rectify wine until the Spiritus Vini ignites gunpowder → *Volatile*
+ Evaporate the remainder to honey thickness in a copper kettle; mix with coal dust; retort in sand → *Phlegm* → *Acetum* → *Oil* → *Coal (C.M.)*
+ Separate oil from vinegar per triturium (glass funnel)
+ Leach the salt from the calcined coal (or combine the raw coal directly into the conjunction)
+ Conjunction and fixation as in rainwater and animal works

*The Tincture of Sal Tartari — A Practical Exercise:*
Rx. Tartar (wine tartrates / grape sediment) — 6 lbs. Divide into: (a) 4 lbs open pot → potter's kiln → calcines to white ash; (b) 2 lbs covered pot → black coal. Lixiviate the white ash → filter → coagulate → melt the salt in a crucible. Add the black coal gradually to the melted salt until it flows dark blue. Pour out quickly into a brass mortar. Powder. Put in alembic with highly rectified Spiritus Vini. Stand day and night in gentle warmth. Pour off the tincture. *Result: true tincture of Sal Tartari — a hundred times more potent than all apothecary waters.*

=== Chapter IX: Anatomia Mineralium — Dissection of Minerals
*Why Minerals Require Stronger Menstrua:*
"Minerals are strongly combined, dessicated bodies which have almost totally chased away their excessive moisture through geological heat. They require not the volatile universal water (rain, dew, Spiritus Vini) but the more fixed universal seed — the Nitre spirit and the Salt spirit — sharpened by their own mineral acidity."

*The Fundamental Rule:*
- Saltpetre / acid spirit does not effectively attack alkalised (strongly congealed) minerals.
- Salt / alkaline spirit does not effectively attack acid minerals.
- *Acid dissolves acid; Alcali dissolves alkaline; hermaphroditic solvent attacks both.*
- Rule: "Identify whether the mineral is acid (dominated by acidity, not yet strongly congealed: ♄, ☽, bismuth), alkaline (strongly congealed Acidum = coagulated: ☉, ♂, bloodstone, emery, talc), or hermaphroditic (Acidum has begun to congeal but remains half-and-half: Vitriol, ♂, ☿)."

*The Fourfold Classification of Minerals:*
1. *Red and white metals:* ♄, ♃, ♂, ☉, Vitriol, ☽ — use Vitriolic Menstruum for red; Alum Menstruum for white.
2. *Marcasite minerals:* ☿, Bismuth, Zinc, Gold marcasite, Silver marcasite, Iron marcasite — dissolve in their specific marcasitical menstruum.
3. *Fixed embryonised sulphurs:* Bloodstone (haematite), emery, bolus (iron clay), talc, lodestone (magnetite), zinc blende, calamine, tutia — most strongly alkalised; require the sharpest Menstruum or preliminary calcination with sulphur.
4. *Volatile embryonised sulphurs:* Arsenic, bismuth flowers, pyrites, orpiment, quartz sand, volatile marcasites — less strongly congealed; dissolve more readily.

*Preparation of the Vitriolic Radical Menstruum (the Key Mineral Solvent):*
Rx. Oil of Vitriol (distilled vitriol spirit) — 1 lb. Pour over white-calcined Vitriol (iron or copper) — 1 lb. Set in a retort; distil the spirit off *gently* in sand (third degree maximum; do not calcine). The Vitriol lies like butter. Cohobate: pour 1 lb fresh spirit upon it, dissolve one day and one night, distil to one-third remaining. Again pour 3 lbs fresh spirit over 1 lb of the concentrated Vitriol. Dissolve and digest. Distil: most rises with the spirit. Cohobate until all has gone over without residue. Drive over per se once, twice, or three times. *Result: the right Radical Menstruum* — will reduce all red Astra (iron, copper, gold, red sulphurs) to their prima materia. "It will turn and reduce all red Astra in primam materiam and make them equal to itself."

*Why the Common Method Fails:* Most practitioners mix Vitriol with raw saltpetre and distil. This is wrong: "When saltpetre meets the Vitriol in heat, the Vitriol has a burning sulphur which is adverse to the saltpetre and chases its spirit away too quickly before it can attack and dissolve the Vitriol. Consequently, the Aqua Fortis goes over taking the volatile sulphur, while what stays behind is only more congealed Vitriol — alarmed and sweating in the fire." The correct order: distil the Aqua Fortis from the calcined Vitriol *gently*, not the reverse.

*Why Solvents Fail at Marcasites (The Saturation Principle):* When too much alkaline solvent (Spirit of Salt, Alcali) is added to Aqua Fortis before applying it to mineral: the Alcali fills the Pores (empty interspaces) of the Aqua Fortis, weakening it so that it cannot attack the marcasite. "The emptier the Pori of the Menstruum are, the more it can absorb and dissolve. The more filled they are, the less it absorbs." Practical rule: use minimum Alcali additive, and increase concentration of the solvent as much as possible by dephlegmation.

*The Mineral Prima Materia as Vitriolic/Aluminous Salt:* When any ore is dissolved in its appropriate Menstruum and distilled to one-third, the crystallisation in the cellar produces the ore's *prima materia*: a vitriolic or aluminous salt. This is the *first reversible step* — the ore has become what it was before it was marcasite. "Neither the sulphur, nor the arsenic, nor the marcasite, nor the metal has been taken from it — all its vital spirits are in the Liquor together."

=== Chapter X: Arbor Dulcificationis — The Tree of Sweetening
*The Macrocosmic Model of Sweetening:* Nature herself sweetens the mineral corrosives through the Tree of Sweetening, visible in the atmosphere: Corrosive mineral vapours rise from the earth's centre. They deposit their strongest corrosive component on the rock walls of mines (too corrosive to rise further — this becomes vitriol and alum). The remaining milder vapours rise to plant roots. What the plant kingdom does not retain rises further into the air, where animals breathe it and transform it into their own food and animal nature. *"This is the Arbor Dulcificationis — the natural order of progressive sweetening from mineral → plant → animal."*

*Why Minerals Cannot Be Given Directly to Animals:* The mineral is still corrosive at its root. It must be turned into a plant first (specified and sweetened through plant matter) before an animal can consume it without harm. Intermediary is mandatory: mineral → plant → animal. "Minerals do not jump directly to the animal quality without being harmed."

*The Modus Dulcificandi (The Technique of Sweetening) — Full Protocol:*

Preparations (three separate fractions):
+ *Animal Volatile:* Putrefied urine → distil volatile spirit + salt → rectify of grosser Phlegm until clear, crystalline, pure. Preserve.
+ *Animal Acidum:* From the residue of the urine distillation, evaporate to honey thickness; mix with leached ashes; retort in sand → grosser Phlegm + Acidum + oil. Separate oil by glass funnel. Filter the Acidum + volatile salt. Rectify through ash twice. Preserve.
+ *Plant Acidum (Acetum):* Good old wine → distil Spiritus Vini (rectify until it ignites gunpowder). Take wine residue, evaporate to honey thickness in copper kettle. Mix with coal dust. Retort in sand → Phlegm → wine vinegar (Acetum) → thick stinking oil. Separate oil from vinegar by funnel. Rectify vinegar through ash two or three times. Preserve.

Sweetening Procedure:
- Rx. Corrosive mineral (dry or liquid) — 1 part. Prepared Acidum (Plant + Animal combined) — 3 parts. Set in Bain Marie in a low alembic. Distil to oily consistency: a pure Phlegm / Aqua Recolacea rises; the acidity and salt remain with the corrosive. Test the remaining oil on the tongue. *If not yet sweet enough, pour again 3 parts Acidum, distil again to oil. Repeat until satisfactorily sweet.*
- When sweet enough: pour 3 parts prepared Spiritus Vini upon it. Set in Bain Marie. Distil to oil. *The oil becomes sweeter still.* Repeat twice more with fresh Spiritus Vini. Each addition of Spiritus Vini deepens the sweetness and renders the medicine more homogeneous with human nature.
- Final result: a *Quintessence / Magisterium / Arcanum Minerale* which "all animals and plants can consume without the least danger." When coagulated: liquid like butter in warmth, solid like ice when cold, dissolves like sugar in all moistures, *cannot be precipitated*.

#doctrine[
  *Kirchweger's doctrinal claim on sweetening:* "The word dulce must not be changed in the alchemical understanding but rather be and remain nomine, re, and actu dulce. Sweet is sweet and must be sweet like honey and sugar, if it is to be called sweet. Consequently, you should make your medicines so that they are truly sweet and not comparatively so." Many alchemists called their product "sweet" when it merely no longer burned the tongue on contact. Kirchweger demands actual organoleptic sweetness — because this is the chemical sign that the corrosive has truly been transformed from the mineral into the plant nature, and the plant nature into the animal. The transition is not cosmetic but substantial.
]

*Sal Metallorum est Lapis Philosophorum:* "The salt of the metals is the Philosophers' Stone and the basis of the whole Art — and concealed in it are the ☿ and the Sulphur." When this salt is turned into oil by sweetening, it is called Sulphur; its internally working spirit is ☿; then Sulphur, Salt, and ☿ are together. When this oil is coagulated back into salt by gentle distillation of moisture: in heat it flows steadily like wax; in cold it stands like ice; in all moistures it dissolves like sugar without any precipitation. *"This is then a most effective medicine, capable of healing all sicknesses."*

=== Chapter XI: Of the Alkahest — or *Alka Est*
*The Origin of the Alkahest Search:* Recognising the fundamental problem — that acid solvents destroy alkaline minerals and vice versa — the philosophers searched for a single universal solvent that would attack both acid and alkaline subjects indiscriminately. Such a subject, they reasoned, must be *hermaphroditic* — containing both natures, associating with either, and remaining undiminished after dissolving its subject.

*The Classical Helmontian Alkahest:* Van Helmont claimed a *liquor alkahest* which dissolved all subjects without any corrosive, without weakening its virgin purity — an *Ens Simplicissimum*. Eirenaeus Philalethes, Starkey, and Brother Belmont concluded it was likely prepared from a *urinous or urinary salt*, given its properties. Van Helmont himself said: *"It was a very simple substance."*

*Kirchweger's Critique of the Alkahest Myth:* "Many laboratory workers produce the Alkahest themselves, but because they do not know how to apply it, they reject the master-key to the fortress." The Alkahest is not a magic solution that operates without corrosive — the very name *Acetum Acerrimum* (sharpest vinegar) reveals its nature. "Don't you know Latin? What does *acerrimum* mean? It means *sharp*." Any truly universal solvent must contain within itself both the Acid and the Alkaline principles united — which means it IS a corrosive, but a balanced, hermaphroditic one.

*The Philosophical Alkahest = The Spiritus Mundi Concentrated:* The true universal Alkahest of the philosophers is the *Mercurius Vitae* of Basilius Valentinus — the quintum elementum — the fifth essence of the whole mineral and universal Nature. "They forged it partly with animal water, partly with plant, mineral, or universal water — and they found that if they made this water sharp and spiritual, the swifter the result was achieved."

*The Three Forms of the Hermaphroditic Universal Menstruum:*
1. *Acetum Acerrimum / Acidum Metallicum Philosophorum:* Quicksilver turned into salt, then into water by repeated action with sharp mineral solvents and various Salia (animal, vegetable, mineral, universal, in varying combinations). The sharper the philosopher sharpened his ☿, the more powerfully it dissolved. Named also: *Acheronticum, Infernalem, Circulatum Majus*.
2. *Via Igne Solo (Without Salt):* ☿ turned into water solely by fire, then sharpened with animal or vegetable waters alone (avoiding mineral corrosives out of fear of producing a basilisk). This route succeeds but more slowly.
3. *Kirchweger's Hermaphroditic Menstrua:* The vitriolic-salt Radical Menstruum described in Chapter IX — which already attacks both acid and alkaline subjects when properly concentrated, because the Vitriol is hermaphroditic by nature (as defined in Chapter IX: "I count among the hermaphroditic nature all those minerals where the acidity has begun to congeal but has remained half-and-half, such as Vitriol, ♂, ☿").

*The Four Classes of Menstrua and Their Failures:*
| Menstruum | Dissolves | Fails At |
|-----------|-----------|----------|
| Volatile only (rain, dew, Spiritus Vini) | Nothing hard | All congealed bodies — extracts only, does not dissolve |
| Acidum only (Azoth, plant/animal vinegar) | Open, acid-dominated minerals | Alkaline and strongly congealed stones |
| Alcali only (volatile or fixed alkali) | Alkaline subjects | Acid minerals |
| Combined (Volatile + Acid + Alkali together) | Open minerals | Hard, strongly congealed ore — all four together dissolve little; each kills the others |

*The True Radical Menstruum:* "It is not really to be found in the mineral kingdom but must be sought elsewhere in Nature" — meaning in the point where the mineral's inherent acidity is still free and hermaphroditic (the Vitriolic spirit before it is fully alkalised into ore). *Aperta jam porta, intra in conclave, amice* — the door is open; enter the chamber, friend.

*Final Practical Prescription for the Philosophers' Stone:* "Bring metals and minerals back into their primary matter by any Menstruum — mercurial, sulphurous, saline, whichever works fastest. Turn the metal back into a salty nature: vitriolic, aluminous, or mineral salt that dissolves without undissolved earth in wine vinegar or Spiritus Vini. Then dissolve that salt in the sweetening Acidum (Chapter X). The more often you dissolve with fresh Acidum and Spiritus Vini and coagulate again, the sweeter and more volatile they become. Distil to a sweet oil. Coagulate gently in ash: liquid like wax in warmth, solid like ice in cold, dissolves like sugar in all moistures, cannot be precipitated. It penetrates everywhere like smoke. This is the Quintessence, Magisterium, and Arcanum — both sweet and sweet-acting."

FINIS — PART II

=== Practical Initiate Applications (Year 2)

*Foundational — Universal Prototype:*
- Complete three-separation work on collected rainwater (the full procedure from the main Chapter V). Choose which of the three Ways to follow based on available equipment. At minimum, perform the Via Naturae Ipsissima (Way II).
- Obtain the Quinta Essentia and verify by the stone-test: sealed in a retort, heated through four degrees, it flows as a clear liquid stone; after cooling, it shatters the retort like glass.

*Animal Kingdom:*
- Prepare the Quintessence of urine (human or large animal): putrefaction → separation → three fractions → conjunction in proper order → coagulation → Quinta Essentia.
- Observe the Evestrum experiment: dissolved Quintessence + Phlegma in a warm alembic → the shape of the animal appears. Study what conditions cause its appearance and dissolution.

*Plant Kingdom:*
- Perform the wine dissection (canonical plant prototype): Spiritus Vini → Acetum → oil → Sal Tartari → Quintessence. Taste each fraction and document their organoleptic qualities and physiological effects.
- Make the tincture of Sal Tartari with the coal sulphur (the "rejected" fraction). Compare its colour and potency to the tincture made from the white calcined ash alone.

*Mineral Kingdom:*
- Prepare the Vitriolic Radical Menstruum from iron vitriol and its own spirit (Chapter IX method — not the common saltpetre mixture). Test its action on calcined iron ♂, then compare to the common Aqua Fortis method. Observe the difference.
- Begin the Arbor Dulcificationis (Chapter X): prepare all three fractions (animal volatile, animal acid, plant acid). Apply to a sample of crystallised vitriol. Perform three rounds of sweetening and test the product on the tongue at each round.

*On Fire Degrees — Critical Practical Canon:*
Set furnaces with 4-6 registers (adjustable dampers). Open 2-3 at the start to initiate the process; close back to one open damper as the material begins flowing. *Never rush the degree.* If the process stops, open one additional register; if it restarts, close the previous one. "In this way one cannot go wrong." The error of overheating: the volatile oil rises and coats the entire retort; a noble liquid part is lost and cannot be recovered. The rule: when you notice the slightest hint of acidity in the vapour from the head, immediately cool everything — the vinegar has begun to rise.
